The Bank of Industry (BoI) yesterday invested N3.5 billion in Ketron investment Limited, a Nigerian company owned  by property firm Persianas Investment Limited. The deal followed last year’s acquisition of ShopRite, Africa’s largest food retailer, from Shoprite International Limited, which sold its 100 per cent shareholding in Retail Supermarkets Nigeria Limited (RSNL) to Ketron. Nigerian businessman Tayo Amusan owns Persianas Investment Limited, and he is the Chairman of Ketron Investment Limited.   Nigeria, others need $25b to deliver universal energy access     ‘Fashion industry revenue spinner’     Raising cashew production   The BoI investment  was contained in the bank’s 2021  yearly results published on its website yesterday. According to its financials cited by The Nation, BoI plans to hold in the long term for strategic reasons. The terms of the deal, it was learnt, included a franchise agreement which secures the right of RSNL to continue to use the Shoprite brand. The deal also included an administration and services agreement which provide RSNL with administration and technical support from the Shoprite Group for an initial  five-year period. Prior to the sale of the retail brand, which launched its operations in Lagos in December 2005, Shoprite had expanded to 25 outlets across 11 Nigerian states and the Federal Capital Territory (FCT).